## Tech founder portfolio sites weaponize anti-design

Analysis of elite founder sites—Patrick Collison, Naval Ravikant, Sam Altman, Balaji Srinivasan—reveals a deliberate rejection of traditional personal branding. Their design statement: *I'm too busy building the future to optimize my personal brand.*

**The anti-hero pattern defines this space.** Patrick Collison's site has zero hero images—just a vertical text list of intellectual topics (Fast, Growth, Questions). Sam Altman uses bare-bones Posthaven. Naval Ravikant's nav.al is pure text and audio. These founders **organize by ideas, not achievements**.

| Element | Elite Founder Pattern | Generic Consultant Pattern |
|---------|----------------------|----------------------------|
| Hero section | None or minimal text | Full-screen photo + tagline |
| Photography | Absent or buried | Professional headshots |
| Social proof | Implicit/linked interviews | Logo bars, testimonials |
| CTA | Understated text link | Prominent buttons, pop-ups |
| Navigation | Topic-based text only | Visual icons, dropdowns |

**The underlying philosophy:** Credibility is established through depth of thinking displayed, not credentials listed. About pages are buried or minimal. Content is organized by intellectual topics rather than career achievements. Email addresses appear as plain text, not contact forms.

